Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Trim the @butternut squash{1}, halve lengthways, then scoop out the seeds (no need
to peel). Cut into 1cm chunks and pop onto a large #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with oil, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out
in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and cooked through,
~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Pour the @water{150%ml} for the rice (see pantry for amount) into a medium
#saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g}, @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once
boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still
covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to
serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

While everything cooks, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on
medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{260%g} and season with @salt{}
and @pepper{}. Cook until browned all over, ~{4-5%minutes}. Turn occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its
> packaging.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the chicken is browned, add the garlic and @tikka masala paste{75%g} to the
pan. Fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @tomato passata{1}, @chicken stock paste{10%g} and @water{75%ml} for the
curry (see pantry for amount) to the pan.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium. Simmer until the sauce
reduced by half and the chicken is cooked through, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Stir in the @creme fraiche{75%g} and cook until piping hot, then remove from the
heat.

Once the squash is roasted, gently stir it through the curry.

Add a splash of water to loosen if you feel if needs it. Taste and add salt and
pepper if needed.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then share between your bowls and top with
your chicken tikka masala.

Enjoy!